  <span id="freeText2321023814983434669" style="display:none">Glue (2001) is a return to the locations, themes and episodic form of Trainspotting, telling the stories of Andrew “Gally” Galloway, Carl “N-SIGN” Ewart, Billy “Business” Birrell, and Terry “Juice” Lawson, spanning several decades in their lives and the bonds that held them both together and apart. <br /><br />At the turn of the millennium, Irvine Welsh embodies a more disconsolate tone of writing, struck by the increasingly atomised nature of society. Compared to earlier novels, Welsh allows the story to become less interesting, instead affording all his attention on bare, honest characterisation. This book is really a book purely about his characters, and they are so skillfully drawn that you cannot put the book down. Few contemporary writers have reached such a complex and interesting level of character styling that Welsh achieves with apparent ease.<br /><br />Glue also allows for the exploration of topics such as the emergence of late 90s neoliberalism, class struggle and the changing landscape of working class communities - old, prophetic truths now seem plastic. How music scenes have changed, + the effects this had also had on drugs.<br /><br />Equal parts distressing and comforting, Welsh explores what it means to have a group of friends (examining at great length the mawkish art of chatting shit to and with them) and the questionable value of such relationships in modern life. Hilarious, grimly honest, disgusting and disturbing. <br /><br />"Typical fuckin Pape stronghold, ah goes. One ay the great myths aboot Scotland is that it's Protestant v. Catholic. The truth is that it's anti-Catholic v. Catholic. Maist anti-Catholics have never been tae a church ootside weddings and funerals. Naw, ah never believed in that Protestant and Catholic shite, it's a load ay nonsense, but these fuckin Pape cunts should come in tae the twentieth century, it has tae be said. And it's good tae noise up they Hibby bastards occasionally as well, even if not one person here is really Catholic. Ah think Birrell's half-Catholic, like me, but ah'm no sure.<br />— Wis wonderin when ye wir gaunny come oot wi the first sectarian shite ay the day . . . mind you, it's ten o'clock already so yuv done awright, Billy tells ays. Billy's been soakin up the sun but eh gits up and smacks the back ay ma heid, which hurts mair thin ah lit oan. That cunt's goat heavy hands n ah'm dizzy. Bastard. Ah look oot ower the gairdin and take a deep breath ay air. Aye, ah think Billy's Ma might be Catholic, like mine.<br /> — Mind you, it wis a bit itchy before last night, Terry says, moving things on. Ah'm quite glad cause ah dinnae want tae get intae an argument aboot who's goat the biggest support (us, used tae be thaim), the hardest mob (thaim, used tae be us), whether thir's mair or less scruffs, yuppies, bigots, pubs, hoors, ravers, AIDS, schools, shoaps or hoaspitals in Leith or Gorgie. Fuck aw that. It's a fuckin hoaliday." <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /><br /><br /></span>
